The paper proposes a method for sensor drift correction in electronic noses using discriminative subspace projection. This involves reducing the dimensionality of the data while preserving the discriminative information. This is a common problem in machine learning and falls under the category of dimensionality reduction. The paper also mentions the use of label information to minimize within-class variance and maximize between-class variance, which suggests a classification problem. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.CV (Computer Vision), cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), and cs.SD (Sound).
